# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flight-management-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flight-management-systems/aircraft-flight-manual] The information within an AFM is also referred to as Technical Airworthiness Data (TAWD).
[src:flight-management-systems/aircraft-flight-manual] A typical flight manual will contain the following: operating limitations, Normal/Abnormal/Emergency operating procedures, performance data and loading information.
[src:flight-management-systems/aircraft-flight-manual] Originally, an AFM would follow whichever format and order the manufacturer felt appropriate.
[src:flight-management-systems/aircraft-flight-manual] Eventually, the General Aviation Manufacturers Association came to an agreement to standardize in GAMA Specification No.
[src:flight-management-systems/aircraft-flight-manual] 1 the format of AFM's for general aviation airplanes and helicopters known as the Pilot's Operating Handbook (POH).
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] The acronym RNAV originally stood for "random navigation," reflecting the initial concept of flexible routing, though the term now refers to a precisely defined and controlled method.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] This flexibility enables more direct routes, potentially saving flight time and fuel, reducing congestion, and facilitating flights to airports lacking traditional navigation aids.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] RNAV achieves this by integrating information from various navigation sources, including ground-based beacons (station-referenced navigation signals), self-contained systems like inertial navigation, and satellite navigation (like GPS).
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] In the United States, RNAV was developed in the 1960s, and the first such routes were published in the 1970s.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] RNAV was reintroduced after the large-scale introduction of satellite navigation.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] The continuing growth of aviation increases demands on airspace capacity, making area navigation desirable due to its improved operational efficiency.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] RNAV systems evolved in a manner similar to conventional ground-based routes and procedures.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] A specific RNAV system was identified and its performance was evaluated through a combination of analysis and flight testing.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] For land-based operations, the initial systems used very high frequency omnidirectional radio range (VOR) and distance measuring equipment (DME) for estimating position; for oceanic operations, inertial navigation systems (INS) were employed.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Airspace and obstacle clearance criteria were developed based on the performance of available equipment, and specifications for requirements were based on available capabilities.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Such prescriptive requirements resulted in delays to the introduction of new RNAV system capabilities and higher costs for maintaining appropriate certification.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] To avoid such prescriptive specifications of requirements, an alternative method for defining equipment requirements has been introduced.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] This enables the specification of performance requirements, independent of available equipment capabilities, and is termed performance-based navigation (PBN).
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Thus, RNAV is now one of the navigation techniques of PBN; currently the only other is required navigation performance (RNP).
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] RNP systems add on-board performance monitoring and alerting to the navigation capabilities of RNAV.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] As a result of decisions made in the industry in the 1990s, most modern systems are RNP.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Many RNAV systems, while offering very high accuracy and possessing many of the functions provided by RNP systems, are not able to provide assurance of their performance.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Recognising this, and to avoid operators incurring unnecessary expense, where the airspace requirement does not necessitate the use of an RNP system, many new as well as existing navigation requirements will continue to specify RNAV rather than RNP systems.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] It is therefore expected that RNAV and RNP operations will co-exist for many years.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] However, RNP systems provide improvements in the integrity of operation, permitting possibly closer route spacing, and can provide sufficient integrity to allow only the RNP systems to be used for navigation in a specific airspace.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] The use of RNP systems may therefore offer significant safety, operational and efficiency benefits.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] While RNAV and RNP applications will co-exist for a number of years, it is expected that there will be a gradual transition to RNP applications as the proportion of aircraft equipped with RNP systems increases and the cost of transition reduces.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] RNAV specifications include requirements for certain navigation functions.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] 5. appropriate failure indication of the RNAV system including its sensors.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] The inability to achieve the required lateral navigation accuracy may be due to navigation errors related to aircraft tracking and positioning.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] The three main errors are path definition error (PDE), flight technical error (FTE) and navigation system error (NSE).
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] The distribution of these errors is assumed to be independent, zero-mean and Gaussian.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Therefore, the distribution of total system error (TSE) is also Gaussian with a standard deviation equal to the root sum square (RSS) of the standard deviations of these three errors.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] PDE occurs when the path defined in the RNAV system does not correspond to the desired path, i.e. the path expected to be flown over the ground.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Use of an RNAV system for navigation presupposes that a defined path representing the intended track is loaded into the navigation database.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] In these cases, the navigation database contains a point-to-point desired flight path, but cannot account for the RNAV system defining a fly-by or fly-over path and performing a maneuver.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] A meaningful PDE and FTE cannot be established without a defining path, resulting in variability in the turn.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Also, a deterministic, repeatable path cannot be defined for paths based on heading and the resulting path variability is accommodated in the route design.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] FTE relates to the air crew or autopilot's ability to follow the defined path or track, including any display error (e.g.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Course Deviation Indicator (CDI) centering error).
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] FTE can be monitored by the autopilot or air crew procedures and the extent to which these procedures need to be supported by other means depends, for example, on the phase of flight (i.e. take-off, climb, cruise, descent, landing) and the type of operations.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Such monitoring support could be provided by a map display.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] NSE refers to the difference between the aircraft's estimated position and actual position.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Longitudinal performance implies navigation against a position along a track (e.g.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] However, at the present time, there are no navigation specifications requiring 4-D control, and there is no FTE in the longitudinal dimension.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] The current navigation specifications define requirements for along-track accuracy, which includes NSE and PDE.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] The along-track accuracy affects position reporting (e.g.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] "10 NM to ABC") and procedure design (e.g. minimum segment altitudes where the aircraft can begin descent once crossing a fix).
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] An RNAV specification is designated as RNAV X, e.g.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] The expression 'X' (where stated) refers to the lateral navigation accuracy in nautical miles, which is expected to be achieved at least 95% of the flight time by the population of aircraft operating within the airspace, route or procedure.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] There are no RNAV approach specifications.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Manual or automated notification of an aircraft's qualification to operate along an air traffic services (ATS) route, on a procedure or in an airspace, is provided to ATC via the flight plan.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Flight plan procedures are specified in appropriate ICAO documents.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Under ICAO’s performance-based navigation (PBN) concept, RNAV specifications identify required accuracy, integrity, availability, continuity, and functionality without prescribing specific sensors.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] Where on-board performance monitoring and alerting is required, the specification is designated RNP rather than RNAV.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] This framework allows civil aviation authorities to update technology (e.g., GNSS with SBAS/GBAS or GNSS-inertial integration) while keeping operational requirements stable and harmonized across regions.
[src:flight-management-systems/area-navigation] RNAV includes eligibility and use on RNAV routes (including Q-routes and T-routes) and RNAV terminal procedures such as standard instrument departures (SIDs) and standard terminal arrival routes (STARs).
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] An **autothrottle** (automatic throttle; also known as **autothrust**, **A/T**, or **A/THR**) is a system that allows a pilot to control the power setting of an aircraft's engines by specifying a desired flight characteristic, rather than manually controlling the fuel flow.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] The autothrottle can greatly reduce the pilots' workload and help conserve fuel and extend engine life by metering the precise amount of fuel required to attain a specific target indicated air speed, or the assigned power for different phases of flight.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] A/T and AFDS (Auto Flight Director Systems) can work together to fulfill the whole flight plan.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] There are two parameters that an A/T can maintain, or try to attain: speed and thrust.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] In speed mode the throttle is positioned to attain a set target speed, subject to safe operating margins.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] For example, if the pilot selects a target speed which is slower than stall speed, the autothrottle system maintains a speed above the stall speed.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] In the thrust mode the engine is maintained at a fixed power setting according to the different flight phases.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] For example, during takeoff, the A/T maintains constant takeoff power until takeoff mode is finished.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] During climb, the A/T maintains constant climb power; in descent, the A/T reduces the setting to the idle position, and so on.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] When the A/T is working in thrust mode, speed is controlled by pitch (or the control column), and not by the A/T.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] A radar altimeter feeds data to the autothrottle in this mode.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] On Boeing-type aircraft, A/T can be used in all flight phases from takeoff, climb, cruise, descent, approach, all the way to land or go-around, barring malfunction.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] Taxi is not considered a part of flight, and A/T does not work for taxiing.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] In most cases, A/T mode selection is automatic without the need of any manual selection unless interrupted by pilots.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] According to Boeing-published flight procedures, A/T is engaged before the takeoff procedure and is automatically disconnected two seconds after landing.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] During flight, manual override of A/T is always available.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] A release of manual override allows A/T to regain control, and the throttle will go back to the A/T commanded position except for two modes (Boeing type aircraft): IDLE and THR HLD.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] In these two modes, the throttle will remain at the manual commanded position.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] A primitive autothrottle was first fitted to later versions of the Messerschmitt Me 262 jet fighter late in World War II.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] However, the first commercial airplane with this system (named AutoPower) was the DC-3 (since 1956).
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] The first version was able to keep a constant angle of attack but speed-only during approach.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] When the possibility of maintaining speed during an entire flight was introduced, it led to the creation of the modern autothrottle.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] The RA-5C Vigilante used an autothrottle actuated by the input from accelerometers installed in the tail which caused the throttle to be sensitive to movement of the stabilator.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] This allowed the pilot to adjust the throttle setting during landing approach by stick input alone.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] Shortly after AutoPower's success, two companies, Sperry (now part of Honeywell) and Collins started competing in the development of an autothrottle, with more and more liners and business jets being equipped with it.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] Today, it is often linked to a flight management system.
[src:flight-management-systems/autothrottle] FADEC is an extension of the autothrottle concept and controls many other parameters besides fuel flow.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] A **flight management system** (**FMS**) is a fundamental component of a modern airliner's avionics.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] An FMS is a specialized computer system that automates a wide variety of in-flight tasks, reducing the workload on the flight crew to the point that modern civilian aircraft no longer carry flight engineers or navigators.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] A primary function is in-flight management of the flight plan.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Using various sensors (such as GPS and INS often backed up by radio navigation) to determine the aircraft's position, the FMS can guide the aircraft along the flight plan.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] From the cockpit, the FMS is normally controlled through a control display unit (CDU) that incorporates a small screen and keyboard or touchscreen.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The FMS sends the flight plan for display to the electronic flight instrument system (EFIS), navigation display (ND), or multifunction display (MFD).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The FMS can be summarised as being a dual system consisting of the **flight management computer** (FMC), CDU and a cross talk bus.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The modern FMS was introduced on the Boeing 767, though earlier navigation computers existed.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Now, systems similar to FMS exist on aircraft as small as the Cessna 182.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] In its evolution an FMS has had many different sizes, capabilities and controls.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] However certain characteristics are common to all FMSs.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The navigation database contains the elements from which the flight plan is constructed.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] These are defined via the ARINC 424 standard.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The navigation database (NDB) is normally updated every 28 days, in order to ensure that its contents are current.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Each FMS contains only a subset of the ARINC / AIRAC data, relevant to the capabilities of the FMS.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Waypoints can also be defined by the pilot(s) along the route or by reference to other waypoints with entry of a place in the form of a waypoint (e.g. a VOR, NDB, ILS, airport or waypoint/intersection).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The flight plan is generally determined on the ground, before departure either by the pilot for smaller aircraft or a professional dispatcher for airliners.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] It is entered into the FMS either by typing it in, selecting it from a saved library of common routes (Company Routes) or via an ACARS datalink with the airline dispatch center.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] During preflight, other information relevant to managing the flight plan is entered.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] This can include performance information such as gross weight, fuel weight and center of gravity.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] It will include altitudes including the initial cruise altitude.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] For aircraft that do not have a GPS, the initial position is also required.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The pilot uses the FMS to modify the flight plan in flight for a variety of reasons.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Significant engineering design minimizes the keystrokes in order to minimize pilot workload in flight and eliminate any confusing information (Hazardously Misleading Information).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The FMS also sends the flight plan information for display on the Navigation Display (ND) of the flight deck instruments Electronic Flight Instrument System (EFIS).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The flight plan generally appears as a magenta line, with other airports, radio aids and waypoints displayed.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Some FMSs can calculate special flight plans, often for tactical requirements, such as search patterns, rendezvous, in-flight refueling tanker orbits, and calculated air release points (CARP) for accurate parachute jumps.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Once in flight, a principal task of the FMS is obtaining a position fix, i.e., to determine the aircraft's position and the accuracy of that position.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Simple FMS use a single sensor, generally GPS in order to determine position.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] But modern FMS use as many sensors as they can, such as VORs, in order to determine and validate their exact position.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Some FMS use a Kalman filter to integrate the positions from the various sensors into a single position.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The FMS constantly crosschecks the various sensors and determines a single aircraft position and accuracy.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The accuracy is described as the Actual Navigation Performance (ANP) a circle that the aircraft can be anywhere within measured as the diameter in nautical miles.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Modern airspace has a set required navigation performance (RNP).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The aircraft must have its ANP less than its RNP in order to operate in certain high-level airspace.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Given the flight plan and the aircraft's position, the FMS calculates the course to follow.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The pilot can follow this course manually (much like following a VOR radial), or the autopilot can be set to follow the course.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The FMS mode is normally called LNAV or Lateral Navigation for the lateral flight plan and VNAV or vertical navigation for the vertical flight plan.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] VNAV provides speed and pitch or altitude targets and LNAV provides roll steering command to the autopilot.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Sophisticated aircraft, generally airliners such as the Airbus A320 or Boeing 737 and other turbofan powered aircraft, have full performance Vertical Navigation (VNAV).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The purpose of VNAV is to predict and optimize the vertical path.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Guidance includes control of the pitch axis and control of the throttle.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The FMS needs to have a comprehensive flight and engine model in order to have the data required to do this.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The function can create a forecast vertical path along the lateral flight plan using this information.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The aircraft manufacturer is usually the only source of this comprehensive flight model.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The vertical profile is constructed by the FMS during pre-flight.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Together with the lateral flight plan, it makes use of the aircraft's starting empty weight, fuel weight, center of gravity, and cruising altitude.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The first step on a vertical course is to rise to cruise height.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Vertical limitations such as "At or ABOVE 8,000" are present in some SID waypoints.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Reducing thrust, or "FLEX" climbing, may be used throughout the ascent to spare the engines.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Each needs to be taken into account when making vertical profile projections.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Implementation of an accurate VNAV is difficult and expensive, but it pays off in fuel savings primarily in cruise and descent.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] In cruise, where most of the fuel is burned, there are multiple methods for fuel savings.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] As an aircraft burns fuel it gets lighter and can cruise higher where there is less drag.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Step climbs or cruise climbs facilitate this.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] VNAV can determine where the step or cruise climbs (in which the aircraft climbs continuously) should occur to minimize fuel consumption.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Performance optimization allows the FMS to determine the best or most economical speed to fly in level flight.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] This is based on the cost index, which is entered to give a weighting between speed and fuel efficiency.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The cost index is calculated by dividing the per-hour cost of operating the plane by the cost of fuel.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Generally a cost index of 999 gives ECON speeds as fast as possible without consideration of fuel and a cost index of zero gives maximum fuel economy while disregarding other hourly costs such as maintenance and crew expenses.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] ECON mode is the VNAV speed used by most airliners in cruise.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] RTA or required time of arrival allows the VNAV system to target arrival at a particular waypoint at a defined time.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] This is often useful for airport arrival slot scheduling.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] In this case, VNAV regulates the cruise speed or cost index to ensure the RTA is met.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The first thing the VNAV calculates for the descent is the top of descent point (TOD).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] This is the point where an efficient and comfortable descent begins.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Normally this will involve an idle descent, but for some aircraft an idle descent is too steep and uncomfortable.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The FMS calculates the TOD by “flying” the descent backwards from touchdown through the approach and up to cruise.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] It does this using the flight plan, the aircraft flight model and descent winds.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] For airline FMS, this is a very sophisticated and accurate prediction, for simple FMS (on smaller aircraft) it can be determined by a “rule of thumb” such as a 3 degree descent path.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] From the TOD, the VNAV determines a four-dimensional predicted path.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] As the VNAV commands the throttles to idle, the aircraft begins its descent along the VNAV path.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] If either the predicted path is incorrect or the downpath winds different from the predictions, then the aircraft will not perfectly follow the path.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] The aircraft varies the pitch in order to maintain the path.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Since the throttles are at idle this will modulate the speed.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Normally the FMS allows the speed to vary within a small band.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] After this, either the throttles advance (if the aircraft is below path) or the FMS requests speed brakes with a message, often "DRAG REQUIRED" (if the aircraft is above path).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] On Airbus aircraft, this message also appears on the PFD and, if the aircraft is extremely high on path, "MORE DRAG" will be displayed.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] On Boeing aircraft, if the aircraft gets too far off the prescribed path, it will switch from VNAV PTH (which follows the calculated path) to VNAV SPD (which descends as fast as possible while maintaining a selected speed, similar to OP DES (open descent) on Airbuses.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] An ideal idle descent, also known as a “green descent” uses the minimum fuel, minimizes pollution (both at high altitude and local to the airport) and minimizes local noise.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] While most modern FMS of large airliners are capable of idle descents, most air traffic control systems cannot handle multiple aircraft each using its own optimum descent path to the airport, at this time.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-management-system] Thus the use of idle descents is minimized by Air Traffic Control.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Flight planning requires accurate weather forecasts so that fuel consumption calculations can account for the fuel consumption effects of head or tail winds and air temperature.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Safety regulations require aircraft to carry fuel beyond the minimum needed to fly from origin to destination, allowing for unforeseen circumstances or for diversion to another airport if the planned destination becomes unavailable.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Furthermore, under the supervision of air traffic control, aircraft flying in controlled airspace must follow predetermined routes known as airways (at least where they have been defined), even if such routes are not as economical as a more direct flight.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Within these airways, aircraft must maintain flight levels, specified altitudes usually separated vertically by 1,000 or 2,000 ft (300 or 610 m), depending on the route being flown and the direction of travel.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] When aircraft with only two engines are flying long distances across oceans, deserts, or other areas with no airports, they have to satisfy additional ETOPS safety rules to ensure they can reach an emergency airport if one engine fails.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] When computer flight planning replaced manual flight planning for eastbound flights across the North Atlantic, the average fuel consumption was reduced by about 450 kg (1,000 lb) per flight, and the average flight times were reduced by about 5 minutes per flight.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Some commercial airlines have their own internal flight planning system, while others employ the services of external planners.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] A licensed flight dispatcher or flight operations officer is required by law to carry out flight planning and flight watch tasks in many commercial operating environments (e.g., US FAR §121, Canadian regulations).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] These regulations vary by country but more and more countries require their airline operators to employ such personnel.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The basic purpose of a flight planning system is to calculate how much trip fuel is needed in the air navigation process by an aircraft when flying from an origin airport to a destination airport.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The way in which reserve fuel is determined varies greatly, depending on airline and locality.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Except for some US domestic flights, a flight plan normally has an alternate airport as well as a destination airport.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The alternate airport is for use in case the destination airport becomes unusable while the flight is in progress (due to weather conditions, a strike, a crash, terrorist activity, etc.).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] This means that when the aircraft gets near the destination airport, it must still have enough alternate fuel and alternate reserve available to fly on to the alternate airport.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Since the aircraft is not expected at the alternate airport, it must also have enough holding fuel to circle for a while (typically 30 minutes) near the alternate airport while a landing slot is found.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] It is often considered a good idea to have the alternate some distance away from the destination (e.g., 185 km (100 nmi; 115 mi)) so that bad weather is unlikely to close both the destination and the alternate; distances of up to 960 kilometres (520 nmi; 600 mi) are not unknown.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] There is often more than one possible route between two airports.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Subject to safety requirements, commercial airlines generally wish to minimise costs by appropriate choice of route, speed, and height.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Various names are given to weights associated with an aircraft and/or the total weight of the aircraft at various stages.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] When twin-engine aircraft are flying across oceans, deserts, and the like, the route must be carefully planned so that the aircraft can always reach an airport, even if one engine fails.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The applicable rules are known as ETOPS (ExTended range OPerationS).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The general reliability of the particular type of aircraft and its engines and the maintenance quality of the airline are taken into account when specifying how long such an aircraft may fly with only one engine operating (typically 1–3 hours).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Flight planning systems must be able to cope with aircraft flying below sea level, which will often result in a negative altitude.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] For example, Amsterdam Schiphol Airport has an elevation of −3 metres.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The surface of the Dead Sea is 417 metres below sea level, so low-level flights in this vicinity can be well below sea level.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Flight plans mix metric and non-metric units of measurement.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The particular units used may vary by aircraft, airline, and location across a flight.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Since 1979, the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) has recommended a unification of units of measurement within aviation based on the International System of Units (SI).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] However, a termination date for completion of metrication has not been established.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Distances are nearly always measured in nautical miles, as calculated at a height of 32,000 feet (9,800 m), compensated for the fact that the earth is an oblate spheroid rather than a perfect sphere.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Aviation charts always show distances as rounded to the nearest nautical mile, and these are the distances that are shown on a flight plan.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Flight planning systems may need to use the unrounded values in their internal calculations for improved accuracy.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Fuel measurement will vary on the gauges fitted to a particular aircraft.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The most common unit of fuel measurement is kilograms; other possible measures include pounds, UK gallons, US gallons, and litres.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] When fuel is measured by weight, the specific gravity of the fuel used is taken into account when checking tank capacity.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] There has been at least one occasion on which an aircraft ran out of fuel due to an error in converting between kilograms and pounds.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] In this particular case the flight crew managed to glide to a nearby runway and land safely (the runway was one of two at a former airport then being used as a dragstrip).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Many airlines request that fuel quantities be rounded to a multiple of 10 or 100 units.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] This can cause some interesting rounding problems, especially when subtotals are involved.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Safety issues must also be considered when deciding whether to round up or down.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The altitude of an aircraft is based on the use of a pressure altimeter (see flight level for more detail).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The heights quoted here are thus the nominal heights under standard conditions of temperature and pressure rather than the actual heights.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] All aircraft operating on flight levels calibrate altimeters to the same standard setting regardless of the actual sea level pressure, so little risk of collision arises.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] In most areas, height is reported as a multiple of 100 feet (30 m), i.e.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] When cruising at higher altitudes aircraft adopt flight levels (FLs).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Flight levels are altitudes corrected and calibrated against the International Standard Atmosphere (ISA).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] These are expressed as a three-figure group e.g., FL320 is 32,000 ft (9,800 m) ISA.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] In most areas, the vertical separation between aircraft is either 1,000 or 2,000 ft (300 or 610 m).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] In Russia, China and some neighbouring areas, altitudes are measured in metres.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The vertical separation between aircraft is either 300 metres or 600 metres (about 1.6% less than 1,000 or 2,000 feet).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Until 1999, the vertical separation between aircraft flying at high altitudes on the same airway was 2,000 feet (610 m).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Since then there has been a phased introduction around the world of reduced vertical separation minimum (RVSM).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] This cuts the vertical separation to 1,000 feet (300 m) between flight levels 290 and 410 (the exact limits vary slightly from place to place).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Since most jet aircraft operate between these heights, this measure effectively doubles the available airway capacity.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] To use RVSM, aircraft must have certified altimeters, and autopilots must meet more accurate standards.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] In a flight plan, a Mach number of "Point 82" means that the aircraft is travelling at 0.820 (82%) of the speed of sound.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The widespread use of global positioning systems (GPS) allows cockpit navigation systems to provide air speed and ground speed more or less directly.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] INS has been present in civil aviation for a few decades and is mostly used in medium to large aircraft as the system is fairly complex.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The weight of an aircraft is most commonly measured in kilograms, but may sometimes be measured in pounds, especially if the fuel gauges are calibrated in pounds or gallons.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Many airlines request that weights be rounded to a multiple of 10 or 100 units.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Great care is needed when rounding to ensure that physical constraints are not exceeded.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] When chatting informally about a flight plan, approximate weights of fuel and/or aircraft may be referred to in tons.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] This "ton" is generally either a metric tonne or a UK long ton, which differ by less than 2%, or a short ton, which is about 10% less.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] A route is a description of the path followed by an aircraft when flying between airports.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Most commercial flights will travel from one airport to another, but private aircraft, commercial sightseeing tours, and military aircraft may do a circular or out-and-back trip and land at the same airport from which they took off.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Aircraft fly on airways under the direction of air traffic control.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] An airway has no physical existence, but can be thought of as a motorway in the sky.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] On an ordinary motorway, cars use different lanes to avoid collisions, while on an airway, aircraft fly at different flight levels to avoid collisions.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] One can often see planes passing directly above or below one's own.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Charts showing airways are published and are usually updated every 4 weeks, coinciding with the AIRAC cycle.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] AIRAC (Aeronautical Information Regulation and Control) occurs every fourth Thursday, when every country publishes its changes, which are usually to airways.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Each airway starts and finishes at a waypoint, and may contain some intermediate waypoints as well.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Waypoints use five letters (e.g., PILOX), and those that double as non-directional beacons use three or two (TNN, WK).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Airways may cross or join at a waypoint, so an aircraft can change from one airway to another at such points.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] A complete route between airports often uses several airways.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Where there is no suitable airway between two waypoints, and using airways would result in a somewhat roundabout route, air traffic control may allow a direct waypoint-to-waypoint routing, which does not use an airway (often abbreviated in flight plans as "DCT").
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Most waypoints are classified as *compulsory reporting points*; that is, the pilot (or the onboard flight management system) reports the aircraft's position to air traffic control as the aircraft passes a waypoint.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Note that airways do not connect directly to airports.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Special routes known as *ocean tracks* are used across some oceans, mainly in the Northern Hemisphere, to increase traffic capacity on busy routes.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Unlike ordinary airways, which change infrequently, ocean tracks change twice a day, so as to take advantage of favourable winds.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Flights going with the jet stream may be an hour shorter than those going against it.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Ocean tracks may start and finish about 100 miles offshore at named waypoints, to which a number of airways connect.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Tracks across northern oceans are suitable for east–west or west–east flights, which constitute the bulk of the traffic in these areas.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] There are a number of ways of constructing a route.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] All scenarios using airways use SIDs and STARs for departure and arrival.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Any mention of airways might include a very small number of "direct" segments to allow for situations when there are no convenient airway junctions.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] In some cases, political considerations may influence the choice of route (e.g., aircraft from one country cannot overfly some other country).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Even in a free-flight area, air traffic control still requires a position report about once an hour.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Flight planning systems organise this by inserting geographic waypoints at suitable intervals.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] For a jet aircraft, these intervals are 10 degrees of longitude for eastbound or westbound flights and 5 degrees of latitude for northbound or southbound flights.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] In free-flight areas, commercial aircraft normally follow a *least-time-track* so as to use as little time and fuel as possible.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] A great circle route would have the shortest ground distance, but is unlikely to have the shortest air distance, due to the effect of head or tail winds.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] A flight planning system may have to perform significant analysis to determine a good free-flight route.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Calculation of fuel requirements (especially trip fuel and reserve fuel) is the most safety-critical aspect of flight planning.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Fuel calculation must take many factors into account.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The air temperature affects the efficiency/fuel consumption of aircraft engines.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The wind may provide a head- or tailwind component, which in turn will increase or decrease the fuel consumption by increasing or decreasing the air distance to be flown.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] These forecasts are generally issued every 6 hours and cover the subsequent 36 hours.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The GRIB format superseded the earlier ADF format in 1998–99.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] intervals; this interval was large enough to miss some storms completely, so calculations using ADF-predicted weather were often not as accurate as those that can be produced using GRIB-predicted weather.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The particular route to be flown determines the ground distance to cover, while winds on that route determine the air distance to be flown.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Each inter-waypoint portion of an airway may have different rules as to which flight levels may be used.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Total aircraft weight at any point determines the highest flight level which can be used.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Cruising at a higher flight level generally requires less fuel than at a lower flight level, but extra climb fuel may be needed to get up to the higher flight level (it is this extra climb fuel and the different fuel consumption rate that cause discontinuities).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Almost all the weights mentioned above in "Overview and basic terminology" may be subject to minimum and/or maximum values.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Due to stress on the wheels and undercarriage when landing, the maximum safe landing weight may be considerably less than the maximum safe brake-release weight.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] In such cases, an aircraft that encounters some emergency and has to land immediately after taking off may have to circle for a while to use up fuel, or else jettison some fuel, or else land immediately and risk having the undercarriage collapse.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Further, the fuel tanks have a maximum capacity.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] On some occasions, commercial flight planning systems find that an impossible flight plan has been requested.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The aircraft cannot possibly reach the intended destination, even with no cargo or passengers, since the fuel tanks are not big enough to hold the amount of fuel needed; it would appear that some airlines are over-optimistic at times, perhaps hoping for a (very) strong tailwind.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Note that a large aircraft, such as a jumbo jet, may burn up to 80 tons of fuel on a 10-hour flight, so there is a substantial weight change during the flight.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The weight of fuel forms a significant part of the total weight of an aircraft, so any fuel calculation must take into account the weight of any fuel not yet burned.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Instead of trying to predict the fuel load not yet burned, a flight planning system can handle this situation by working backward along the route, starting at the alternate, going back to the destination, and then going back waypoint by waypoint to the origin.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] A more detailed outline of the calculation follows.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Several (possibly many) iterations are usually required, either to calculate interdependent values such as reserve fuel and trip fuel, or to cope with situations where some physical constraint has been exceeded.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] In the latter case it is usually necessary to reduce the payload (less cargo or fewer passengers).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Some flight planning systems use elaborate systems of approximate equations to simultaneously estimate all the changes required; this can greatly reduce the number of iterations needed.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] If an aircraft lands at the alternate, in the worst case it can be assumed to have no fuel left (in practice there will be enough reserve fuel left to at least taxi off the runway).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Hence a flight planning system can calculate alternate holding fuel on the basis that the final aircraft weight is the zero fuel weight.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Since the aircraft is circling while holding, there is no need to take wind into account for this or any other holding calculation.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] For the flight from destination to alternate, a flight planning system can calculate alternate trip fuel and alternate reserve fuel on the basis that the aircraft weight on reaching the alternate is zero fuel weight plus alternate holding.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] A flight planning system can then calculate any destination holding on the basis that the final aircraft weight is zero fuel weight plus alternate holding plus alternate fuel plus alternate reserve.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] For the flight from origin to destination, the weight on arrival at the destination can be taken as zero fuel weight plus alternate holding plus alternate fuel plus alternate reserve plus destination holding.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] A flight planning system can then work back along the route, calculating the trip fuel and reserve fuel one waypoint at a time, with the fuel required for each inter-waypoint segment forming part of the aircraft weight for the next segment to be calculated.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] At each stage and/or at the end of the calculation, a flight planning system must carry out checks to ensure that physical constraints (e.g., maximum tank capacity) have not been exceeded.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Problems mean that either the aircraft weight must be reduced in some way or the calculation must be abandoned.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Calculation can then proceed forward along the route, waypoint by waypoint.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] On reaching the destination, the actual trip fuel can be compared with the estimated trip fuel, a better estimate made, and the calculation repeated as required.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Commercial airlines generally wish to keep the cost of a flight as low as possible.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] For any given route, a flight planning system can reduce cost by finding the most economical speed at any given altitude and by finding the best altitude(s) to use based on the predicted weather.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Such local optimisation can be done on a waypoint-by-waypoint basis.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Commercial airlines do not want an aircraft to change altitude too often (among other things, it may make it more difficult for the cabin crew to serve meals), so they often specify some minimum time between optimisation-related flight level changes.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] To cope with such requirements, a flight planning system must be capable of non-local altitude optimisation by simultaneously taking a number of waypoints into account, along with the fuel costs for any short climbs that may be required.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] When there is more than one possible route between the origin and destination airports, the task facing a flight planning system becomes more complicated, since it must now consider many routes in order to find the best available route.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Many situations have tens or even hundreds of possible routes, and there are some situations with over 25,000 possible routes (e.g., London to New York with free-flight below the track system).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The amount of calculation required to produce an accurate flight plan is so substantial that it is not feasible to examine every possible route in detail.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] A flight planning system must have some fast way of cutting the number of possibilities down to a manageable number before undertaking a detailed analysis.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] From an accountant's viewpoint, the provision of reserve fuel costs money (the fuel needed to carry the hopefully unused reserve fuel).
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Techniques known variously as **reclear**, **redispatch**, or *decision point procedure* have been developed, which can greatly reduce the amount of reserve fuel needed while still maintaining all required safety standards.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] These techniques are based on having some specified intermediate airport to which the flight can divert if necessary; in practice such diversions are rare.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The use of such techniques can save several tons of fuel on long flights, or it can increase the payload carried by a similar amount.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] A reclear flight plan has two destinations.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The *final destination* airport is where the flight is really going to, while the *initial destination* airport is where the flight will divert to if more fuel is used than expected during the early part of the flight.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The waypoint at which the decision is made as to which destination to go to is called the *reclear fix* or *decision point*.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] On reaching this waypoint, the flight crew make a comparison between actual and predicted fuel burn and check how much reserve fuel is available.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] If there is sufficient reserve fuel, then the flight can continue to the final destination airport; otherwise the aircraft must divert to the initial destination airport.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The initial destination is positioned so that less reserve fuel is needed for a flight from the origin to the initial destination than for a flight from the origin to the final destination.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Under normal circumstances, little if any of the reserve fuel is actually used, so when the aircraft reaches the reclear fix it still has (almost) all the original reserve fuel on board, which is enough to cover the flight from the reclear fix to the final destination.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The idea of reclear flights was first published in *Boeing Airliner* (1977) by Boeing engineers David Arthur and Gary Rose.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The original paper contains a lot of magic numbers relating to the optimum position of the reclear fix and so on.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] These numbers apply only to the specific type of aircraft considered, for a specific reserve percentage, and take no account of the effect of weather.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Despite all the effort taken to optimise flight plans, there are certain circumstances in which it is advantageous to file suboptimal plans.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] In busy airspace with a number of competing aircraft, the optimum routes and preferred altitudes may be oversubscribed.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] This problem can be worse in busy periods, such as when everyone wants to arrive at an airport as soon as it opens for the day.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] If all the aircraft file optimal flight plans then to avoid overloading, air traffic control may refuse permission for some of the flight plans or delay the allocated takeoff slots.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] To avoid this a suboptimal flight plan can be filed, asking for an inefficiently low altitude or a longer, less congested route.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Once airborne, part of the pilot's job is to fly as efficiently as possible so he/she might then try to convince air traffic control to allow them to fly closer to the optimum route.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] This might involve requesting a higher flight level than in the plan or asking for a more direct routing.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] If the controller does not immediately agree, it may be possible to re-request occasionally until they relent.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Alternatively, if there has been any bad weather reported in the area, a pilot might request a climb or turn to avoid weather.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Even if the pilot does not manage to revert to the optimal route, the benefits of being allowed to fly may well outweigh the cost of the suboptimal route.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Although VFR flights often do not require filing a flight plan, a certain amount of flight planning remains necessary.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The captain has to make sure that there will be enough fuel on board for the trip and sufficient reserve fuel for unforeseen circumstances.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] Weight and centre of gravity must remain within their limits during the whole flight.
[src:flight-management-systems/flight-planning] The captain must prepare an alternate flight plan for when landing at the original destination is not possible.
[src:flight-management-systems/multi-function-display] A **multifunction display** (**MFD**) is a small-screen (CRT or LCD) surrounded by multiple soft keys (configurable buttons) that can be used to display information to the user in numerous configurable ways.
[src:flight-management-systems/multi-function-display] MFDs originated in aviation, first in military aircraft, and later were adopted by commercial aircraft, general aviation, automotive use, motorsports use, and shipboard use.
[src:flight-management-systems/multi-function-display] Often, an MFD will be used in concert with a primary flight display (PFD), and forms a component of a glass cockpit.
[src:flight-management-systems/multi-function-display] MFDs are part of the digital era of modern planes or helicopter.
[src:flight-management-systems/multi-function-display] The first MFDs were introduced by air forces in the late 1960s and early 1970s; an early example is the F-111D (first ordered in 1967, delivered from 1970–73).
[src:flight-management-systems/multi-function-display] The advantage of an MFD over analog display is that an MFD does not consume much space in the cockpit, as data can be presented in multiple pages, rather than always being present at once.
[src:flight-management-systems/multi-function-display] For example, the cockpit of RAH-66 "Comanche" does not have analog dials or gauges at all.
[src:flight-management-systems/multi-function-display] All information is displayed on the MFD pages.
[src:flight-management-systems/multi-function-display] The possible MFD pages could differ for every plane, complementing their abilities (in combat).
[src:flight-management-systems/multi-function-display] Many MFDs allow pilots to display their navigation route, moving map, weather radar, NEXRAD, ground proximity warning system, traffic collision avoidance system, and airport information all on the same screen.
[src:flight-management-systems/multi-function-display] MFDs were added to the Space Shuttle (as the glass cockpit) starting in 1998, replacing the analog instruments and CRTs.
[src:flight-management-systems/multi-function-display] The information being displayed is similar, and the glass cockpit was first flown on the STS-101 mission.
[src:flight-management-systems/multi-function-display] In modern automotive technology, MFDs are used in cars to display navigation, entertainment, and vehicle status information.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Area navigation (RNAV) and RNP systems are fundamentally similar.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The key difference between them is the requirement for on-board performance monitoring and alerting.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] A navigation specification that includes a requirement for on-board navigation performance monitoring and alerting is referred to as an RNP specification.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] One not having such a requirement is referred to as an RNAV specification.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Therefore, if ATC radar monitoring is not provided, safe navigation in respect to terrain shall be self-monitored by the pilot and RNP shall be used instead of RNAV.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] RNP also refers to the level of performance required for a specific procedure or a specific block of airspace.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] An RNP of 10 means that a navigation system must be able to calculate its position to within a circle with a radius of 10 nautical miles.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] An RNP of 0.3 means the aircraft navigation system must be able to calculate its position to within a circle with a radius of 3/10 of a nautical mile.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The differences in these systems are typically a function of on-board navigational system redundancies.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] A related term is ANP which stands for "actual navigation performance." ANP refers to the current performance of a navigation system while "RNP" refers to the accuracy required for a given block of airspace or a specific instrument procedure.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Some oceanic airspace has an RNP capability value of 4 or 10.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The level of RNP an aircraft is capable of determines the separation required between aircraft with respect to distance.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] This is not only a major advantage for air traffic operations, but presents a major cost-savings opportunity for airlines flying over the oceans due to less restrictive routing and better available altitudes.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] RNP approaches with RNP values currently down to 0.1 allow aircraft to follow precise three-dimensional curved flight paths through congested airspace, around noise sensitive areas, or through difficult terrain.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] RNP procedures were introduced in the PANS-OPS (ICAO Doc 8168), which became applicable in 1998.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] These RNP procedures were the predecessor of the current PBN concept, whereby the performance for operation on the route is defined (in lieu of flight elements such as flyover procedures, variability in flight paths, and added airspace buffer), but they resulted in no significant design advantages.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] As a result, there was a lack of benefits to the user community and little or no implementation.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] In 1996, Alaska Airlines became the first airline in the world to utilize an RNP approach with its approach down the Gastineau Channel into Juneau, Alaska.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Alaska Airlines Captain Steve Fulton and Captain Hal Anderson developed more than 30 RNP approaches for the airline's Alaska operations.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] In 2005, Alaska Airlines became the first airline to utilize RNP approaches into Reagan National Airport to avoid congestion.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] In April 2009, Alaska Airlines became the first airline to gain approval from the FAA to validate their own RNP approaches.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] On 6 April 2010, Southwest Airlines converted to RNP.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Since 2009, regulators in Peru, Chile, and Ecuador have deployed more than 25 RNP AR approach procedures, designed in conjunction with LAN Airlines.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Benefits included reduction in greenhouse gases emissions and improved accessibility to airports located on mountainous terrain.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The use of RNP AR approaches in Cusco, near Machu Picchu, has reduced cancellations due to foul weather by 60 percent on flights operated by LAN.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Inspired by a 2011 white paper, the ICAO published in November 2018 the Established on RNP-Authorization Required (EoR) standard to reduce separation for parallel runways, improving traffic flow while reducing noise, emissions and distance flown.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Conservative estimates of CO2 emissions savings due to EoR operations at Denver International Airport exceed 1 billion tons as of 2024.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Similar to Denver, it was implemented over three years at Calgary International Airport, lowering the final approach requirement from 20 to 4 mi (32.2 to 6.4 km), before reaching *trajectory-based* operations.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] As 40% of aircraft arriving are equipped to fly RNP-AR, 3,000 RNP-AR approaches per month would save 33,000 miles (53,000 km), and associated with continuous descent, would reduce greenhouse gases emissions by 2,500 metric tons in the first year.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] RNP APCH supports all leg types and path terminators used in standard RNAV, including TF and RF.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] An RNP system utilises its navigation sensors, system architecture, and modes of operation to satisfy the RNP navigation specification requirements.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] It must perform the integrity and reasonableness checks of the sensors and data, and it may provide a means to deselect specific types of navigation aids to prevent reversion to an inadequate sensor.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The RNP type defines the total system error that is allowed in lateral and longitudinal dimensions within a particular airspace.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The total system error, which takes account of navigation system errors, computation errors, display errors and flight technical errors, must not exceed the specified RNP value for 95 percent of the flight time on any part of any single flight.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] RNP requirements may limit the modes of operation of the aircraft, e.g. for low RNP, where flight technical errors is a significant factor, and manual flight by the crew may not be allowed.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Dual system/sensor installations may also be required depending on the intended operation or need.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] An RNAV system capable of achieving the performance requirements of an RNP specification, including monitoring and alerting of Actual Navigation Performance, is referred to as an RNP system.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Because specific performance requirements are defined for each navigation specification, an aircraft approved for a RNP specification is not automatically approved for all RNAV specifications.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Similarly, an aircraft approved for an RNP or RNAV specification having stringent accuracy requirements is not automatically approved for a navigation specification having a less-stringent accuracy requirement.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] For oceanic, remote, enroute and terminal operations, an RNP specification is designated as RNP X, e.g.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Approach navigation specifications cover all segments of the instrument approach.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] RNP specifications are designated using RNP as a prefix and an abbreviated textual suffix, e.g.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] RNP APCH (for RNP approach) or RNP AR APCH (for RNP authorisation required approach).
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The performance monitoring and alerting requirements for RNP 4, Basic-RNP 1 and RNP APCH have common terminology and application.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The net effect of RNP navigation specifications is to provide bounding of the TSE distribution.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Since path definition error is assumed to be negligible, the monitoring requirement is reduced to the other two components of TSE, i.e. flight technical error (FTE) and navigation system error (NSE).
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] It is assumed that FTE is an ergodic stochastic process within a given flight control mode.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] As a result, the FTE distribution is constant over time within a given flight control mode.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Although the TSE can change significantly over time for a number of reasons, including those above, the RNP navigation specifications provide assurance that the TSE distribution remains suitable to the operation.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Typically, the 10−5 TSE requirement provides a greater restriction on performance.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] These characteristics define minimum requirements that must be met, but they do not define the actual TSE distribution.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The actual TSE distribution may be expected to be typically better than the requirement, but there must be evidence on the actual performance if a lower TSE value is to be used.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] It is important that performance monitoring is not regarded as error monitoring.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] A performance monitoring alert will be issued when the system cannot guarantee, with sufficient integrity, that the position meets the accuracy requirement.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] When such an alert is issued, the probable reason is the loss of capability to validate the position data (insufficient satellites being a potential reason).
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] For such a situation, the most likely position of the aircraft at that time is exactly the same position indicated on the pilot display.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Assuming the desired track has been flown correctly, the FTE would be within the required limits and therefore the likelihood of the TSE exceeding twice the accuracy value just prior to the alert is approximately 10−5.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] However, it cannot be assumed that simply because there is no alert the TSE is less than twice the accuracy value: the TSE can be larger.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] An example is for those aircraft that account for the FTE based on a fixed error distribution.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] For such systems, if the FTE grows large, no alert is issued by the system even when the TSE is many times larger than the accuracy value.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] For this reason, the operational procedures to monitor the FTE are important.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Oceanic and remote continental airspace is currently served by two navigation applications, RNAV 10 and RNP 4.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Both rely primarily on GNSS to support the navigation element of the airspace.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] In the case of RNAV 10, no form of ATS surveillance is required.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] In the case of RNP 4, ADS contract (ADS-C) is used.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Continental en-route airspace is currently supported by RNAV applications.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] RNAV 5 is used in the Middle East (MID) and European (EUR) regions, but as of 2008, it is designated as B-RNAV (Basic RNAV in Europe and RNP 5 in the Middle East).
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] In the United States, RNAV 2 supports en-route continental airspace.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] At present, continental RNAV applications support airspace specifications which include radar surveillance and direct controller-to-pilot voice communications.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Existing terminal airspace concepts, which include arrival and departure, are supported by RNAV applications.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] These are currently used in the European (EUR) Region and the United States.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The European terminal airspace RNAV application is known as P-RNAV (Precision RNAV).
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Although the RNAV 1 specification shares a common navigation accuracy with P-RNAV, this regional navigation specification does not satisfy the full requirements of the RNAV 1 specification.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] As of 2008, the United States terminal airspace application formerly known as US RNAV Type B has been aligned with the PBN concept and is now called RNAV 1.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Basic RNP 1 has been developed primarily for application in non-radar, low density terminal airspace.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] In future, more RNP applications are expected to be developed for both en-route and terminal airspace.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Approach concepts cover all segments of the instrument approach, i.e. initial, intermediate, final, and missed approach.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The RNP APCH specifications requiring a standard navigation accuracy of 1.0 NM in the initial, intermediate and missed segments and 0.3 NM in the final segment.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] RNP approaches to 0.3 NM and 0.1 NM at Queenstown Airport in New Zealand are the primary approaches used by Qantas and Air New Zealand for both international and domestic services.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Due to terrain restrictions, ILS approaches are not possible, and conventional VOR/DME approaches have descent restrictions more than 2,000 ft above the airport level.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The RNP approaches and departures follow curved paths below terrain level.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] RNP instrument approach procedures with Authorization Required or **RNP AR** (previously known as Special Aircraft and Aircrew Authorization Required or SAAAR) approach procedures build upon the performance based NAS concept.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The performance requirements to conduct an approach are defined, and aircraft are qualified against these performance requirements.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Conventional obstacle evaluation areas for ground-based navigation aids are based on a predefined aircraft capability and navigation system.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] RNP AR criteria for obstacle evaluation are flexible and designed to adapt to unique operational environments.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] This allows approach specific performance requirements as necessary for an approach procedure.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] The operational requirement can include avoiding terrain and obstacles, de-conflicting airspace or resolving environmental constraints.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] RNP AR APCH is defined as an RNP approach procedure that requires a lateral TSE lower than the standard RNP values on any segment of the approach procedure.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] RNP approaches include capabilities that require special aircraft and aircrew authorization similar to category II/III ILS operations.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] All RNP AR approaches have reduced lateral obstacle evaluation areas and vertical obstacle clearance surfaces predicated on the aircraft and aircrew performance requirements.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] When conducting an RNP AR approach using a line of minima less than RNP 0.3, no single-point-of-failure can cause the loss of guidance compliant with the RNP value associated with the approach.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Typically, the aircraft must have at least dual GNSS sensors, dual flight management systems, dual air data systems, dual autopilots, and a single inertial reference unit.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] When conducting an RNP AR approach with a missed approach less than RNP 1.0, no single-point-of-failure can cause the loss of guidance compliant with the RNP value associated with a missed approach procedure.
[src:flight-management-systems/required-navigation-performance] Manual or automated notification of an aircraft's qualification to operate along an air traffic services (ATS) route, on a procedure or in an airspace is provided to ATC via the flight plan.
